export const MUTATION_DESCRIPTIONS = {
  "physical": {
    "attraction odor": "<p>The mutant constantly gives off a scent that draws carnivores.</p>",
    "body structure change": "<p>This defect is intentionally broad and is left largely to the referee. In general, an essential part of the body is altered in a harmful way, reducing the mutant&#39;s resistance to outside force. Examples include brittle bones caused by a lack of calcium, total loss of body hair that leaves the mutant vulnerable to dust, or a single eye centered in the forehead that ruins depth perception.</p>",
    "chameleon powers": "<p>The mutant can shift body color almost instantly to match surrounding terrain or cover. Once the change is made, no continued concentration is needed. The referee decides how effective the camouflage is in a given situation.</p>",
    "density control": "<p>The mutant can alter the molecular structure of its own body to become denser or less dense. When becoming denser, the body shrinks and armor class improves in direct proportion to the size reduction. A mutant reduced to one-half normal size has twice normal armor class, and one reduced to one-eighth normal size is too dense to be pierced by swords, spears, arrows, and similar weapons. The tradeoff is that movement and reflexes are reduced by the same ratio, so a mutant at one-eighth size also acts at one-eighth normal speed.</p><p>When becoming less dense, the body expands instead. This lowers armor class and physical strength, but increases speed. A mutant at twice normal size has an armor class four classes lower than normal and can move four times as fast. Expansion is limited to double normal size. The change is instantaneous, and there is no limit to how often the mutant may do this.</p>",
    "diminished sense": "<p>One of the mutant&#39;s senses functions below normal levels. Sight, smell, taste, or another sense may be dulled enough to miss threats or hazards that others would notice.</p>",
    "double physical pain": "<p>The mutant is so sensitive to pain that all physical damage it suffers is doubled.</p>",
    "electrical generation": "<p>The mutant can discharge electrical shocks, eel-like, once each melee turn. Anyone touching the mutant takes 3d6 damage.</p>",
    "fat cell accumulation": "<p>The mutant is fat, usually reaching twice normal size. The referee determines how badly this hinders movement and fighting ability. In some cases only particular body parts, such as the head, one arm, or one thigh, are enlarged instead of the whole body.</p>",
    "gas generation: musk": "<p>The mutant has a gas or musk gland similar to a skunk&#39;s. It may expel the secretion at targets within 10 meters. The discharge can repel, render unconscious, or kill, depending on its nature. Possible forms include obscuring gas, irritating gas, paralysis gas, poison gas, poison musk, blinding musk, and similar effects.</p>",
    "heat generation": "<p>The mutant can project beams of searing heat from its hands, paws, tentacles, or similar organs. Each blast inflicts 4d6 damage, has a maximum range of 15 meters, and may be used once every 3 melee turns.</p>",
    "heightened balance": "<p>The mutant keeps its footing in situations where others would fall. It does not tumble into pits, trip over ropes or wires, or land anywhere but on its feet. If undisturbed, it can climb sheer walls and cross tightropes with no chance of falling.</p>",
    "heightened constitution": "<p>This mutation grants 2 additional hit points for every point of Constitution. It also gives the mutant an 18 resistance to poison and adds 3 points to radiation resistance.</p>",
    "heightened dexterity": "<p>The mutant is so agile in combat that its armor class becomes 4. The referee may worsen that armor class when the mutant is heavily encumbered.</p>",
    "heightened hearing": "<p>The mutant can hear and identify even the faintest sound out to 60 meters. Because of this, it cannot be surprised.</p>",
    "heightened precision": "<p>The mutant can spot weak points in enemies and structural flaws in objects. Any weapon it uses inflicts 2 extra dice of damage beyond its normal amount.</p>",
    "heightened smell": "<p>The mutant can separate and identify odors at a distance of up to 60 meters. It cannot be ambushed by non-plant creatures approaching from upwind, though this is different from immunity to surprise. It can track any trail less than a day old across any surface except water. Once it has encountered another being, it can later identify objects and locations associated with that being, such as possessions or campsites.</p>",
    "heightened strength": "<p>With non-powered weapons, the mutant inflicts 3 extra dice of damage beyond normal weapon damage.</p>",
    "heightened taste": "<p>By merely touching a substance with its tongue, the mutant can detect poison and tell whether the substance is edible.</p>",
    "heightened touch": "<p>This mutation improves the mutant&#39;s chance to figure out ancient devices. Given enough time, it can also feel out weak points in objects. That makes the ability useful for opening locks, working safes, or escaping confinement.</p>",
    "heightened vision": "<p>The mutant can see clearly and identify objects at distances of up to 3 kilometers. It can also see into both the infrared and ultraviolet spectra and is not troubled by full daylight.</p>",
    "hemophilia": "<p>Because the mutant lacks proper clotting agents, even small cuts become dangerous. As soon as it loses at least 1 hit point, it begins to bleed and suffers 2 extra hit points of damage every melee round until the wound is stopped and bound.</p>",
    "increased metabolism": "<p>The mutant must spend an unusual amount of time eating. It has to carry extra food while traveling, and in combat it must stop every 5th melee turn and spend 1 full turn eating before it can rejoin the fight. If it does not, it loses 1 point of Physical Strength and 2 hit points every melee turn after that. These losses are temporary unless the mutant dies, and they are recovered at the same rate if the mutant takes time out to eat.</p>",
    "increased speed": "<p>The mutant moves at twice normal speed, completes mental tasks far more quickly than usual, and may strike twice each melee turn in combat.</p>",
    "infravision": "<p>The mutant can see any heat-producing body. At night, that makes the world appear as bright as day. Sudden flashes of heat, such as lasers, explosions, large fires, or even a nearby torch, temporarily blind the mutant. Prolonged exposure to full daylight is also painful.</p>",
    "light generation": "<p>The mutant can emit a brilliant flash of light through its eyes. Even in full daylight, this glare lowers viewers&#39; armor class and chance to hit by 4 points for 1-4 melee turns. The flash is comparable to a camera bulb, so it is not normally useful as steady illumination. Effective range is 10 meters.</p>",
    "multiple body parts": "<p>One normal body part, other than the brain, is multiplied. The mutant might have extra legs, more eyes, or 1-10 additional arms, among other possibilities.</p>",
    "new body parts": "<p>The mutant gains one or more anatomical features not normally found on its kind. Possible examples include a third eye in the back of the head, radiation-sensitive feelers, light-sensitive antennae, pincers, a fur coat, feathers, a radiation-absorbing organ, and similar additions.</p>",
    "no resistance to bacteria": "<p>The mutant has little or no resistance to disease, so infection becomes a major threat. This defect only matters if disease-causing agents exist in the campaign. A dirty wound might turn septic, the scratch of a predator might infect, or a common cold might become pneumonia. Such illnesses can inflict up to 10 points of damage per day and are very difficult to cure.</p>",
    "no resistance to poison": "<p>Any poison is fatal to this mutant unless the proper antidote is administered quickly.</p>",
    "no sensory nerve endings": "<p>The mutant cannot feel pain, which removes the body&#39;s normal warning system. It may fail to notice a surprise strike from behind, an open wound, or even the moment it regains lost hit points. This defect also makes ancient devices harder to understand by adding 2 points to each die roll made to figure out artifacts.</p>",
    "oversized body parts": "<p>One body part is enlarged in a beneficial way, and that part gains a matching boost in performance. Larger eyes might improve sight, for example, or longer legs might increase speed. Only one body part can be affected in this way.</p>",
    "partial carapace": "<p>A thick shell covers the mutant&#39;s back and head. Strikes landing there do only half damage. The mutation also gives the mutant a basic armor class of 6.</p>",
    "photosynthetic skin": "<p>The mutant can manufacture its own food in sunlight or an equivalent light source. If it spends most of its time basking without moving, it heals lost hit points four times faster than normal. The drawback is that heat and cold attacks inflict 1 extra point of damage per die, and the mutant moves at half speed in darkness.</p>",
    "physical reflection": "<p>The mutant&#39;s skin reflects one specific form of energy in random directions instead of absorbing it. The reflection applies to only one category, such as heat, sonic force, radiation, electricity, or a similar energy type.</p>",
    "poor respiratory system": "<p>The mutant has difficulty getting enough oxygen into its bloodstream. It tires easily and must rest after 5 melee turns of combat. If it keeps fighting beyond that point, it faints for 1-6 minutes immediately after the 6th melee turn.</p>",
    "quills/spines": "<p>These defensive growths usually cover the arms or legs. A quill inflicts dagger damage on contact, and some mutants can throw quills as far as 3 meters. Spines are larger and tougher; each one inflicts 3-12 points of damage if it hits, and they may also be thrown. Replacement quills or spines take at least 1 week to regrow.</p>",
    "radiated eyes": "<p>The mutant can fire a radiation blast from its eyes. Roll 3d6 to determine the radiation intensity. The attack has a range of 10 meters and may be used once every 4 melee turns.</p>",
    "regeneration": "<p>The mutant heals and regrows lost hit points at a rate of 1 hit point per day for every 5 kilograms of body weight.</p>",
    "shapechange": "<p>The mutant can alter its outward form to resemble a mammal, insect, or reptile, but gains none of the imitated creature&#39;s abilities. At the start of the campaign, the mutant must choose which of those three broad forms it can mimic. Completing the change takes 2 melee turns of relative inactivity, during which the mutant makes no attacks.</p>",
    "shorter": "<p>To determine the mutant&#39;s height, roll percentile dice twice, treating 00 as 0 rather than 100, and add the two results together. The sum is the mutant&#39;s height in centimeters. This reduced size lowers metabolic rate and noticeably cuts physical combat damage, but also makes the mutant much harder to hit. The referee determines the exact effects.</p>",
    "skin structure change": "<p>The mutant&#39;s skin changes for the worse. Possibilities include thin skin that adds 1 point to each die of damage taken, water-soluble skin that suffers 1 die of damage per melee turn of contact with water, phosphorescent skin that glows enough to reveal position but not enough to illuminate surroundings, or light-sensitive skin that burns for 1-3 dice of damage in bright light.</p>",
    "sonic attack ability": "<p>The mutant can generate damaging high-frequency sound. Every creature except the mutant within a 10 meter radius suffers 3d6 damage; roll the dice once and apply that result to all affected beings. This attack is not selective and may be used once every 4 melee turns.</p>",
    "symbiotic attachment": "<p>The mutant can connect itself to another creature&#39;s nervous system. It must first hit the victim with a natural attacking appendage and then maintain contact for 3 melee turns. Once the link is complete, the mutant has total control of both bodies. If contact is broken, control ends. Restoring that control requires another uninterrupted 3 melee turns of contact.</p>",
    "taller": "<p>Roll 1d6 and add the result to a base height of 2 meters, producing a mutant between 3 and 8 meters tall. For every meter above 2 meters, add 1 point to each damage die inflicted with non-powered melee weapons. For every full 2 meters above 2 meters, subtract 1 point from physical combat attack rolls. Hit points are not changed.</p>",
    "total carapace": "<p>A thick shell covers the mutant&#39;s entire body. All damage against it is halved, and its armor class becomes 4. The shell is cumbersome and reduces movement by one-fourth.</p>",
    "ultravision": "<p>The mutant can see ultraviolet light. In addition to ultraviolet emissions, it can perceive radiation, energy cells, mental mutations that affect the physical environment, and the electrical workings of machines.</p>",
    "vision defect": "<p>The mutant suffers from a serious visual problem such as myopia or astigmatism, though not blindness. It takes a 4 point penalty on attack rolls in combat and has difficulty seeing objects beyond 15 meters.</p>",
    "weight decrease": "<p>The mutant is weakened so badly that all actions are slowed by one-fourth, and Physical Strength is also reduced by one-fourth.</p>",
    "wings": "<p>The mutant grows functional wings and can fly at 12 meters per melee turn. While airborne, it may carry no more than one-fourth of its own body weight. Mutants weighing more than 80 kilograms usually cannot truly fly, though they can still make wing-assisted leaps over walls, trees, and similar obstacles.</p>"
  },
  "mental": {
    "absorption": "<p>The mutant can absorb one specific form of damage, chosen randomly, up to an additional amount equal to its current hit point total. Roll 1d6 to determine the protected form: 1 = cold, 2 = heat, 3 = light, 4 = paralysis rays, 5 = radiation, 6 = mental blasts.</p>",
    "anti-reflection": "<p>Each time the mutant uses a mental power, there is a 25% chance that the effect reverses. A mental attack rebounds onto the mutant instead of the target, and a mental defense protects the opponent instead.</p>",
    "complete mental block": "<p>The mutant is mentally incapable of intentionally seeing or approaching one blocked category: robotic, technological but non-robotic, plant, or animal. It can still behave rationally around the blocked thing, but it cannot use it, touch it, or even notice attacks made by it. The referee should narrow the block to one specific example within the broader type, such as a security robot.</p>",
    "cryokinesis": "<p>The mutant can freeze living tissue, water, or anything else capable of freezing, possibly turning it solid at the referee&#39;s discretion. On the first melee turn it inflicts 1d6 cold damage. With uninterrupted concentration, the damage increases by 1d6 per turn until it reaches 10d6 on the 10th melee turn. Range is 25 meters.</p>",
    "death field generation": "<p>In a single melee turn, this mutation drains all but 1 hit point from every being within 20 meters. The mutant is not harmed by the field, but after using it can do nothing else for 1-20 melee turns while lying nearly unconscious.</p>",
    "de-evolution": "<p>This power regresses a mutant opponent along its ancestral line. Treat it as a mental attack. If it succeeds, the target permanently loses its greatest special ability first, chosen by the referee. On each later melee turn, another special ability is stripped away until the victim is reduced to its original stock. The effect lasts for one combat situation, however long that lasts, has a range of 30 meters, and may be used once per week.</p>",
    "density control (others)": "<p>Use the rules for self-only Density Control from the physical mutation list, but give the effect a range of 30 meters and allow it to be used offensively or defensively on other beings.</p>",
    "directional sense": "<p>The mutant always knows exactly where it is in relation to where it has already been. It can retrace its path at any time, even while blindfolded.</p>",
    "dual brain": "<p>The mutant has two fully functioning brains, even if it does not have two heads. Between them, the mutant may possess as many as 3 additional mental mutations. The second brain gives a -1 bonus on all die rolls made to figure out ancient artifacts. Under mental attack, one brain may suffer the effect while the other keeps the mutant moving and acting normally. The mutant gets two mental saving throws, and if either one succeeds, the attack fails. Both brains use the same Mental Strength score rolled at character creation, but any Mental Strength increase gained by surviving mental attacks is earned at only half the normal rate.</p>",
    "empathy": "<p>The mutant can sense the feelings of others, including fear, pain, hunger, hatred, and similar emotions. It can also impose emotions on any non-intelligent creature, treating such a target as if it had a mental resistance of 12. Range is 30 meters. This can drive a pack away in fear, draw prey closer, and so on.</p>",
    "epilepsy": "<p>The mutant suffers bouts of body paralysis during which it cannot respond to its surroundings. The referee should establish a consistent trigger pattern, such as a 10% chance per melee turn during physical combat or a 25% chance just before a fight begins.</p>",
    "fear impulse": "<p>The mutant has an irrational terror of one subject and cannot look upon it without panicking, dropping everything, and fleeing. Roll 1d6 to determine the source of fear: 1 = a random mutated animal, 2 = a random mutated insect, 3 = a random non-mutated creature, 4 = any robot, 5 = any computer, 6 = any talking plant. If a specific creature is needed, the referee chooses it.</p>",
    "force field generation": "<p>The mutant can create an invisible barrier around its own body, roughly 15 centimeters out from the skin, through which physical objects cannot pass. The field can absorb 5 dice of cumulative damage before collapsing. Once raised, it requires no effort to maintain and lasts up to 1 hour unless destroyed first. Only one force field may be generated every 24 hours.</p>",
    "genius capability": "<p>Roll 1d6 to determine the type of genius involved.</p><table class=\"gw-mutation__table\"><thead><tr><th>Roll</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1-2</td><td>Military genius: gains a +4 bonus to hit with any weapon and inflicts 1 extra die of damage.</td></tr><tr><td>3-4</td><td>Scientific genius: subtract 1 point from each die roll made to figure out ancient artifacts. Any weapon the mutant builds, such as a crossbow, sling, or trap, inflicts 4 extra points of damage on each hit, but takes three times as long to make.</td></tr><tr><td>5-6</td><td>Economic genius: can make triple profit on anything sold and also gains the +3 Charisma bonus of a Pure Strain Human.</td></tr></tbody></table>",
    "heightened brain talent": "<p>The mutant can figure out the workings of any artifact in one-third the usual time, so 10 die rolls on the artifact charts take 40 minutes instead of 2 hours. It also gets two saving throws against mental attacks. If the mutant also has Dual Brain, it does not receive four mental saves. It is impossible to tell this mutant an undetected lie.</p>",
    "heightened intelligence": "<p>Add 4 points to the mutant&#39;s mental resistance rating, to a maximum of 18. Also subtract 2 points from die rolls made to figure out artifacts.</p>",
    "hostility field": "<p>The mutant unconsciously projects an unpleasant field in a 30 meter radius. Any being with an Intelligence of 16 or less, friend or foe, has a 20% chance of wanting to attack the mutant when it first enters the field.</p>",
    "illusion generation": "<p>The mutant can create images directly in the minds of beings within 30 meters. These illusions may include visual, audible, and olfactory elements, and they vanish only when someone tries to touch them.</p>",
    "intuition": "<p>The mutant is subconsciously aware of what an opponent intends to do. This grants +1 on attack rolls with any weapon and adds 3 points to each die of damage inflicted. The mutation cannot be used while any other mental power is being used.</p>",
    "life leech": "<p>The mutant drains life energy from every semi-intelligent or intelligent being, friend or foe, within a 10 meter radius. Increase that radius by 3 meters for every 4 points of Mental Strength the mutant has. Each affected being loses 6 hit points per melee turn, and the mutant gains the same number of hit points. If the mutant later takes damage, subtract it from the leeched hit points first. Any leeched hit points still remaining after combat vanish 24 hours later.</p>",
    "light wave manipulation": "<p>The mutant can make itself and everything it is wearing or carrying invisible, negate the effect of a laser, or create a 1 meter radius patch of total darkness anywhere within 10 meters. It can only make itself invisible, but the darkness and laser-negation effects may be placed anywhere within range.</p>",
    "magnetic control": "<p>By manipulating magnetic fields, the mutant can attract, repel, or otherwise control any inanimate ferrous object. The referee determines effects on powered devices. To see whether control is established, treat the target object as if it had a mental resistance of 12. There is no weight limit. Range is 100 meters, duration is up to 25 melee turns, and the mutation may be used once every 24 hours.</p>",
    "mass mind": "<p>The mutant can empathically join with creatures of the same type or with creatures that share a similar power, such as telepathy, mental blast, or mental control, to increase the effectiveness of its own abilities. The increase is directly proportional to the number of minds participating. For example, two creatures who both have Mental Blast could combine to produce a blast at double strength and twice normal range.</p>",
    "mental blast": "<p>The mutant can launch a mental assault at any being within 15 meters. Each blast inflicts 3d6 damage and may be used every other melee turn.</p>",
    "mental control": "<p>The mutant can take over another being&#39;s body. While control lasts, the mutant experiences all of the target&#39;s senses and is completely unaware of its own body, which remains motionless. If the controlled being is knocked unconscious or dies, the controller suffers the same result. The mutant must be within 15 meters to establish control, but once control is in place, there is no range limit. The mutant may release control and return to its own body whenever it wishes.</p>",
    "mental control over physical state": "<p>The mutant can unconsciously override pain, fatigue, blood loss, and similar physical limits for up to 1 full day. It also heals wounds four times faster than normal. In moments of overwhelming danger, as decided by the referee, the mutant&#39;s Strength, Dexterity, and Speed all double for 5-50 melee turns. This mutation may only be used once per week.</p>",
    "mental defenselessness": "<p>Ignore the mutant&#39;s rolled Mental Strength. It is now 3.</p>",
    "mental defense shield": "<p>The mutant gains 4 points of mental resistance, to a maximum of 18. It also automatically senses the presence of any being with mental powers within 30 meters, whether those powers are currently in use or not.</p>",
    "molecular disruption": "<p>This mutation is powerful and dangerous, and it can only be used rarely. Whether the attempt succeeds or fails, the mutant is left at 1 hit point and half normal movement for 1 full day. Success chance depends on the target: 3% per point of Mental Strength for metal and other dense material, 4% per point for stone and other non-living matter, and 5% per point for living organisms. Up to 50 kilograms of contiguous matter within 30 meters may be destroyed this way. After each use, the referee secretly rolls 1d6 to determine how many days must pass before the mutation has any chance to work again.</p>",
    "molecular understanding": "<p>The mutant immediately understands the weak points of objects and their individual parts. In combat, this grants 1 extra die of damage beyond normal damage. It also allows the mutant to instantly figure out the use of any artifact on Chart A and subtract 2 points from die rolls on the other artifact charts.</p>",
    "multiple damage": "<p>Any damage suffered by the mutant is doubled or even tripled, at the referee&#39;s option. This happens because the mutant believes the harm is worse than it actually is.</p>",
    "planar travel": "<p>The mutant can open a doorway to an alternate plane of existence. The opening is 3 by 3 meters and lasts up to 3 full melee turns, at the mutant&#39;s discretion. The destination plane may or may not be inhabited. Once something enters, it cannot leave again unless the mutant opens another doorway, which makes this a useful power for exile. Only one such door may be opened each week.</p>",
    "poor dual brain": "<p>The mutant has a second brain that interferes with the first. It may seize control of the body at inconvenient times, possess several defects of its own, or sabotage another mental power in a crisis. The referee decides the exact effects and may keep them secret until they become relevant.</p>",
    "precognition": "<p>The mutant can foresee dangerous situations that will personally affect it, but only up to 3 minutes into the future and only with intense concentration. For example, the mutant may look ahead to see what would happen if it opened a certain door, then avoid that outcome by choosing differently. If the vision includes damage to the mutant&#39;s own body, the shock causes immediate damage of 1d6. If the mutant foresees its own death, it immediately takes 2d6 damage and falls unconscious for 3-18 minutes. The referee may limit uses per day, perhaps by rolling 1d4 or 1d6.</p>",
    "pyrokinesis": "<p>The mutant can inflict heat damage on living tissue or anything reasonably flammable, such as wood or plastic, and may eventually set the target ablaze. On the first melee turn the power inflicts 1d6 damage, not necessarily from open flame. With uninterrupted concentration, the damage rises by 1d6 each turn until it reaches 10d6 on the 10th melee turn. The referee determines whether and when fire actually begins. Range is 25 meters.</p>",
    "radar/sonar": "<p>The mutant possesses bat-like or dolphin-like sensing organs, such as oversized ears or antennae, and can move or fly in darkness as if it were seeing normally. It also receives a +2 bonus on all attack rolls. The usual range is 30 meters, but if the mutant also has Heightened Hearing, that range is tripled.</p>",
    "reflection": "<p>Using this power requires complete concentration and stillness. On the 1st melee turn of concentration, the mutant can reflect up to 3 dice of damage of any type back at the beings who caused it. On the 2nd turn, the limit rises to 4 dice, and so on, up to 20 dice on the 16th and final turn. Reflected damage can never exceed the amount originally inflicted. The power may be used once every 24 hours. While it is active, the mutant is still vulnerable to simple incapacitating effects that inflict no dice of damage, such as Light Generation. The mutant may continue reflecting even while taking damage, as long as it takes no other action. While reflection is active, the mutant takes no damage unless the incoming damage exceeds its current reflecting limit.</p>",
    "repulsion field": "<p>This works like Force Field Generation, except the barrier may be created anywhere within 15 meters and can be used to enclose or trap other beings. In all other ways it functions exactly like a force field, and it can also be used around the mutant&#39;s own body if desired.</p>",
    "sound imitation": "<p>This mutation resembles Thought Imitation, but applies to sound. The mutant can reproduce noises it hears and can immediately hurl back a sonic attack after hearing and surviving it. It cannot memorize the sound for later use; it only repeats what it has just heard.</p>",
    "telekinesis": "<p>The mutant can lift and move objects through force of mind, though never itself. The maximum weight is whatever the mutant could physically lift, and it must strain as though it were carrying the load by hand. Only objects within 15 meters may be lifted, and they can stay aloft for only 5 melee turns before the mutant must rest for 5 more melee turns. If the target is a living creature, or an object held by a living creature, resolve the attempt first as a mental attack against that being.</p>",
    "telekinetic arm": "<p>The mutant can manifest a 20 meter long human arm, complete with hand, with Strength 18. It can perform anything a normal human arm and hand can do. The arm must remain visible to the mutant in order to function. Non-powered weapons cannot hit it, but powered weapons that strike it deal normal damage to the mutant.</p>",
    "telekinetic flight": "<p>The mutant can fly at any speed from 1 to 20 meters per second while carrying no more than it could normally carry.</p>",
    "telepathy": "<p>The mutant can read another creature&#39;s thoughts or emotions and send its own in return. The effect ignores language barriers and works on all beings within 10 meters.</p>",
    "teleportation": "<p>The mutant can mentally transfer its body to another place up to 30 kilometers away. It may teleport only itself, never others. If it has not spent at least 8 hours memorizing the destination, there is a 25% chance that arrival inflicts 10d6 damage.</p>",
    "thought imitation": "<p>The mutant can immediately send back any thought or mental attack directed at it, though it still suffers the original effect. It can also perfectly imitate the communication patterns of any creature whose thought processes it knows, even if that creature does not use a language the mutant understands. Returned mental attacks are temporary and cannot be repeated later, but familiar communication patterns can be recalled afterward.</p>",
    "time field manipulation": "<p>This is the power to move through time or to send objects through it. The mutant must have both an Intelligence of 18 and the Heightened Intelligence mutation to possess this ability; otherwise roll another mutation instead. The subject travels through time while remaining in the same physical location on Gamma World.</p><p>Whether the attempt works or not, the energy drain removes one-half of the mutant&#39;s hit points for 1-8 days and cuts its speed in half for 1-12 days. The mutant must be touching whatever it sends through time.</p><p>The following table gives the chance of success for the mutant itself or for any inanimate object that does not belong to another being when sending it into the past:</p><table class=\"gw-mutation__table\"><thead><tr><th>Distance Traveled in Time</th><th>Chance of Success</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1 week</td><td>1-95%</td></tr><tr><td>25 weeks</td><td>41-86%</td></tr><tr><td>1 year</td><td>1-80%</td></tr><tr><td>5 years</td><td>1-75%</td></tr><tr><td>10 years</td><td>1-60%</td></tr><tr><td>25 years</td><td>1-50%</td></tr><tr><td>50 years</td><td>1-30%</td></tr><tr><td>100 years</td><td>1-20%</td></tr><tr><td>250 years</td><td>1-10%</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Material that is part of another being, or belongs to another being, is harder to send. Subtract 10% for metal or powered items, 15% for stone and other inorganic matter, and 20% for biological material such as another creature. To send anything into the future instead of the past, subtract 25% from each entry on the table above. The energy drain still occurs even if the attempt fails.</p>",
    "total healing": "<p>The mutant can restore all of its own lost hit points once every 24 hours, up to 4 times per week.</p>",
    "weather manipulation": "<p>The mutant can alter local weather conditions in the area around it. The new weather persists only while the mutant keeps concentrating. If the mutant is struck in combat, concentration is broken. It must first concentrate for 1 full minute, or 6 melee turns, before the weather starts to shift, and then spend another 2 minutes, or 12 melee turns, to complete the change. The affected area has a radius of 10 kilometers.</p><p>The mutation cannot create a wildly impossible shift, such as turning below-zero conditions directly into a 100 degree heat wave. The possible changes depend on the current weather:</p><table class=\"gw-mutation__table\"><thead><tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Prevailing Condition</th><th>Possible Change</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cloud cover / precipitation</td><td>Clear</td><td>Very clear; partly cloudy or hazy</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud cover / precipitation</td><td>Partly cloudy</td><td>Clear; cloudy</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud cover / precipitation</td><td>Cloudy</td><td>Partly cloudy; misty, light rain, light snow, sleet, or small hail</td></tr><tr><td>Cloud cover / precipitation</td><td>Deep clouds</td><td>Fog, heavy rain, heavy snow, driving sleet, or large hail</td></tr><tr><td>Temperature</td><td>Hot</td><td>Sweltering heat; warm</td></tr><tr><td>Temperature</td><td>Warm</td><td>Hot; cool</td></tr><tr><td>Temperature</td><td>Cool</td><td>Warm; cold</td></tr><tr><td>Temperature</td><td>Cold</td><td>Cool; arctic cold</td></tr><tr><td>Wind</td><td>Calm</td><td>Dead calm; light wind</td></tr><tr><td>Wind</td><td>Light wind</td><td>Calm; strong wind</td></tr><tr><td>Wind</td><td>Strong wind</td><td>Light wind; gale</td></tr><tr><td>Wind</td><td>Gale</td><td>Strong wind; storm</td></tr><tr><td>Wind</td><td>Storm</td><td>Gale; hurricane or typhoon</td></tr></tbody></table><p>All three aspects may be manipulated, but only within the limits shown above. Contradictory combinations, such as fog and strong wind together, are not allowed.</p><p>The base chance to cause one of the listed changes is 90%. If the mutant wants a result one step farther away from current conditions, such as clear weather becoming light rain, the chance drops to 50% and the required concentration and completion times are both doubled. If the mutant wants a result two steps away, such as warm weather becoming arctic cold, the chance falls to 10% and the required times are tripled.</p><p>Roll percentile dice after the initial concentration is complete, but the new conditions do not fully take effect until the weather change has finished. If the attempt fails, either because the roll fails or because the mutant is interrupted after the initial concentration, the mutant must rest for a full week before trying again. This mutation can be used at most once per day.</p>",
    "will force": "<p>By sheer determination, the mutant can double any one of its abilities. It may also be used to grant a +1 bonus on attack rolls instead. This power can be combined with any other mutation. It lasts 1-10 melee turns and may be used only once every 24 hours.</p>"
  },
  "plant": {
    "adaptation": "<p>Once the plant survives a particular attack mode, it becomes permanently immune to that mode. A plant that lives through a laser attack, for example, takes no damage from later laser attacks. This adaptation does not help against physical severing, so swords and axes can still chop off limbs or stalks.</p>",
    "aromatic powers": "<p>Carnivorous plants use this mutation to lure prey. The plant releases a powerful fragrance that can drift as far as 10 kilometers when the wind is favorable. Anyone who smells it believes the plant is their favorite food. Once drawn within 30 meters, a creature does nothing but walk straight toward the plant unless it makes a saving throw against intensity 8 poison that attracts rather than kills.</p>",
    "attraction odor": "<p>The plant&#39;s body or blossoms emit an odor that attracts herbivores.</p>",
    "bacterial symbiosis": "<p>The plant shelters dangerous bacteria just beneath its epidermis. These germs are harmful to humans, humanoid mutants, or any other specific enemy chosen for the plant. If the plant is cut, damaged, or eaten, the bacteria are released and can enter open wounds, causing immediate infection. The referee may invent especially nasty strains for this purpose.</p>",
    "barbed leaves": "<p>These tough leaves are edged with barbs as long as 2.5 centimeters. They normally attack the same way saw-edged leaves do. If the leaves are mounted on a movable plant part, such as a segmented limb, sucker vine, or manipulation vine, that part can attack, inflict damage, and hold or drag the victim with the barbs. Range is limited by the length of the plant part carrying them.</p>",
    "berries": "<p>These mutated berries can have many useful or dangerous effects on humans and humanoid mutants.</p><table class=\"gw-mutation__table\"><thead><tr><th>Roll</th><th>Color</th><th>Effect</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1</td><td>Purple</td><td>Heal 1 die of damage</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>Blue</td><td>Heal all damage</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>Green</td><td>Mental Strength +4 for 1 hour</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>Turquoise</td><td>Poison, random intensity (3d6)</td></tr><tr><td>5</td><td>Orange</td><td>Radiation, random intensity (3d6)</td></tr><tr><td>6</td><td>Orange-yellow</td><td>Radiation resistance +4 for 1 hour</td></tr><tr><td>7</td><td>Red-orange</td><td>Poison antidote for one specific poison intensity only</td></tr><tr><td>8</td><td>Black</td><td>Temporary sonic resistance for 1 hour</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Many other berries are simply edible. Since berries are seasonal, the referee should also limit how long they remain available and effective.</p>",
    "boring tendrils": "<p>These are tough, motile tendrils equipped with acids and abrasive pads that let them bore through almost anything. They can penetrate 5 centimeters of flesh in 1 melee turn, 25 millimeters of wood in 2 melee turns, 5 millimeters of stone in 5 melee turns, 5 millimeters of normal steel in 10 melee turns, and 3 millimeters of duralloy in 10 melee turns.</p>",
    "carnivorous jaws": "<p>The plant grows mouths that inflict 1-8 points of damage per bite. A single plant may have as many as 12 of these jaws, usually placed at the ends of thick, movable stems. A giant Venus flytrap is the classic model.</p>",
    "color sensitivity and imitation": "<p>The plant can change its colors and surface appearance to imitate other kinds of plants. Intelligent plants can also use this ability to operate machinery activated by color bands.</p>",
    "contact poison sap": "<p>The plant&#39;s sap contains poison of random intensity. Once the plant is wounded and the sap is exposed, the poison affects flesh on contact and does not need to enter the victim&#39;s bloodstream.</p>",
    "daylight stasis": "<p>This defect forces the plant into total inactivity during full daylight. By contrast, other plants normally become inactive during darkness, though they may still grow and heal while dark conditions continue.</p>",
    "dissolving juices": "<p>The plant can secrete fluids that inflict 5d6 damage per melee turn to any organic matter they touch.</p>",
    "divisional body segments": "<p>The plant&#39;s trunk, vines, branches, stalks, limbs, or similar structures are segmented like the body or legs of an insect. This grants the plant mobility.</p>",
    "electrical generation": "<p>The plant can build up an electrical charge in its tissues and release it offensively or defensively, like an electric eel. The discharge may be delivered through special vines or by simple contact, and it inflicts as much as 4d6 damage. After a discharge, the plant recharges at a rate of 1 die of shocking power per melee turn. Most plants, 80% of them, do not release another shock until all 4 dice have recharged.</p>",
    "explosive and/or radiated fruit or seeds": "<p>The plant&#39;s seeds, berries, or fruits become explosive or radioactive hazards, with exact strength determined by the referee. Plants that also possess mobility or manipulating vines may hurl these projectiles as missiles. Small bush-sized plants can throw them up to 10 meters, larger plants up to 20 meters, and trees up to 30 meters.</p>",
    "heat generation": "<p>The plant develops special heat organs, usually on top of the plant or at the ends of motile limbs, that fire beams doing 4d6 searing damage. Each beam has a maximum range of 15 meters and may be used once every 3 melee turns. No plant can have more than 3 such organs.</p><p>Unintelligent plants, and plants that lack improved sensory organs, attack anything that comes within range and have a 25% chance to miss each shot outright; if that miss occurs, no attack roll is made. Intelligent plants and plants with superior senses do not suffer that penalty and are not forced to fire immediately.</p>",
    "increased senses": "<p>The plant gains new or improved senses such as sight, hearing, or smell. These senses matter only if the plant can use them through movement, flight, attacks, or some similar behavior.</p>",
    "low fertility": "<p>This sharply reduces reproduction and limits how many such plants can exist in one place. If the mutation is rolled a second time, the plant species becomes extinct.</p>",
    "manipulation vines": "<p>These vines act as dexterous appendages that let the plant handle objects. They are weaker than squeeze vines and inflict no damage by themselves, but they can potentially wield weapons and tools.</p>",
    "mobility": "<p>The plant can walk, crawl, or slither by using motile roots or vines. This does not automatically make the plant intelligent.</p>",
    "new plant parts": "<p>The plant gains new structures such as eyes, ears, arms, an elephant-like trunk, or even a brain and nervous system.</p>",
    "new senses": "<p>Adjustments to normal plant structures give the plant senses equal to those of a human: touch, taste, smell, sight, and hearing. If the plant has no moving parts or defenses, however, these senses may not be very useful.</p>",
    "parasitic attachment": "<p>The plant can connect to another creature&#39;s nervous system and control its body. It must first hit the victim with an appendage such as a tendril, vine, or segmented limb, then maintain contact for 3 melee turns. Once control is established, an unintelligent plant usually uses the victim to defend the plant or serve as food, while an intelligent plant may have more elaborate plans. If contact is broken, control ends immediately.</p>",
    "physical reflection": "<p>The plant&#39;s skin or bark reflects one type of energy away in random directions instead of absorbing it. The reflection applies to only one category, such as heat, sonic force, radiation, or electricity.</p>",
    "poison throwing thorns": "<p>The plant grows 1-100 throwing thorns coated with poison of random intensity. Replacement thorns take at least 1 week to regrow.</p>",
    "poison vines": "<p>These are non-motile, prickly vines that inject poison on contact with flesh. Poison intensity is 3-18 (3d6), with exact details left to the referee.</p>",
    "radiated plant fiber": "<p>Certain plant parts emit radiation of intensity 3-12. The radiation reaches as far as 50 meters and does not harm the plant itself.</p>",
    "razor-edged leaves": "<p>These are smaller, sharper versions of saw-edged leaves and usually cover the entire plant.</p>",
    "saw-edged leaves": "<p>The plant has large, toothed, motile leaves that it usually keeps hidden until something disturbs them. Once triggered, the leaves slash viciously at anything thrust among them. A branch or vine fitted with these leaves usually carries 6-8 of them, and each such branch inflicts 1d4 damage per melee turn. They cut only cloth, flesh, and other soft materials.</p>",
    "seed mobility": "<p>Motile tendrils let the plant&#39;s seeds move around as separate organisms. If appropriate, the seeds may have their own physical or mental powers, or remain telepathically linked to the parent. In especially nasty cases, the seeds of a carnivorous plant may lurk around campsites or sleeping places and then root themselves in sleeping victims during the night.</p>",
    "size decrease": "<p>The plant becomes 1-20 times smaller than normal, determined by 1d20, to a minimum of one-twentieth normal size.</p>",
    "size increase": "<p>The plant becomes 1-20 times larger than normal, determined by 1d20.</p>",
    "sonic attack ability": "<p>When stimulated or disturbed, the plant emits a high-frequency shriek that damages exposed tissue. All creatures within a 10 meter radius, except the plant itself and others of its own kind nearby, take 3d6 damage. The attack may be used once every 4 melee turns.</p>",
    "squeeze vines/roots": "<p>These vines or roots are stronger and faster than tangle vines and can rapidly wrap around a target. Each one crushes for 2 dice of damage per melee turn and does not release its grip unless it is cut away from the plant. Such vines or roots are at least 5 meters long and may grow far longer.</p>",
    "spore cloud and/or shooting seeds": "<p>When touched or otherwise triggered, the plant releases spores or fires seeds from its flower or sporangium. The result may be direct damage, rooting in a victim, or any other effect the referee decides is appropriate.</p>",
    "sucker vines": "<p>These are manipulation vines covered in tiny suction cups. Each vine has a Dexterity of 18.</p>",
    "tangle vines": "<p>These weak vines move slowly and have very little strength. Even so, a large patch can trip or entangle victims, and can still wind around and crush creatures that have only 1 hit point remaining.</p>",
    "temperature sensitivity": "<p>The plant suffers 2 extra points per die from heat attacks, cold attacks, and energy weapon attacks.</p>",
    "texture change": "<p>The plant&#39;s normal outer covering is replaced with something tougher, such as scales, hide, or metallic-looking plates. Whatever the new texture is, it must be an improvement.</p>",
    "thorns/spines": "<p>The plant is covered in large spikes 15-30 centimeters long. If they puncture a victim, they inflict dagger damage. Determine a random number of spikes for each plant, but always give it more than 5.</p>",
    "throwing thorns": "<p>The plant has 1-100 dart-like thorns that it can fire to a distance of up to 10 meters, depending on its sensory awareness. Each thorn inflicts dagger damage if it hits. Replacements take at least 1 week to grow.</p>",
    "wings/gas bag": "<p>The plant has structures that let it drift or slowly fly from one area to another. Speed and direction depend mostly on the wind. Some carnivorous plants use the mutation to travel in search of food.</p>"
  }
};

/**
 * Normalize a mutation name for lookup. Mirror of the same function
 * in the build script so pack-build and runtime resolution produce
 * identical keys.
 */
export function normalizeMutationName(rawName) {
  let name = String(rawName ?? "").trim().toLowerCase();
  name = name.replace(/\s*\(d\)\s*$/i, "");
  name = name.replace(/\s+-\s+/g, ": ");
  name = name.replace(/\s{2,}/g, " ");
  return name.trim();
}

export function mutationDescriptionFor(subtype, name) {
  const bucket = MUTATION_DESCRIPTIONS[subtype];
  if (!bucket) return null;
  return bucket[normalizeMutationName(name)] ?? null;
}
